    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27.79-80_0001"/>
               
                <fw type="curatorial">79</fw>
              
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        225 Willard Way, Ithaca, <hi rend="caps">N.Y.</hi>
                        Mar. 24, 1959
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear John:-</salute></opener> <p>I am so <hi rend="underline">glad</hi> that you had that wonderful trip. What a country Oregon is! You write about it with the same enthusiasm that I feel, as always I include Washington, too, for that land <del/> is also marvelous. And then you <del>saw</del> here "....beside
                    <lb/>
                    <del>"</del>The Umpqua where it <unclear>bitters</unclear> with the tide", with all the attached memories of Jed Smith. And to see your wife's friend, and to have such <add>a</add> nice experience <unclear>returning</unclear> &#8212; Well, it almost reads as if too good to be true. And yet it was. How very fortunate. I always, as you know, rejoice when something good happens to you.</p>
                    
                <p>Winter is leaving us reluctantly, <del/><add>O</add> so reluctantly. <unclear>Save</unclear> two weeks ago we had a whole day of Snowfall turning all the landscape into a region of pure white wonder. And only a few days ago, the temperature was <hi rend="underline">16</hi>. But today the sun shone and a warmer <unclear>trend</unclear> held sway. And someday the wave of spring will dash over these hills, leaving green spray on the lowliest bush and tallest tree.</p>
                    
                <p>I lent your record to <unclear>that</unclear> graduate student who entertained us while you were here. He and his
                    
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27.79-80_0002"/>
                        
                <fw type="curatorial">80</fw>     
                    
                    wife like it so much. And as for me, I wish <del>so much</del><add><hi rend="underline">rep.</hi></add> that you <del>could</del><add>would</add> make other records. Is there any chance of Orpheus doing so? That is really a must while your voice is strong, and the <unclear/> music of your song comes <unclear/> so well. How I want to hear you recite Crazy Horse, Sitting Bull, and your lyrics.</p>
                    
                <p>We are about to have a week of vacation. We shall spend part of it visiting our daughter Kathleen and her family, who live just west of Harrisburg, Pa.</p>
                
                <p>Do you have a few <del>and</del> autographed copies of your Easter poem that you could spare? every now + then I run across a friend who would treasure a copy. I never give one except to such a person. <hi rend="underline">Now don't send any unless you can spare it.</hi> I should not wish to <unclear/> you.</p>
                
                <p>Well, dear friend, present often in my thoughts and always in my heart, I am, as, ever and always.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>Slade</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <opener><hi rend="caps">P.S.</hi></opener> <p>Nita valued your thought of her and your wish that the three of us <add>could</add> have a nightcap together. I certain join in that wish. We'd have some good bourbon too.</p>
                </postscript>
                    
            </div1>
